        <name>7.4.5.3 (not in quiz): Determinant method &#9472; Inverse of a 3 x 3 matrix</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Use the determinant method to find the inverse of the following matrices&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\[\bf A = {@A@},\] \[\bf B = {@B@}.\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div&gt;(a) \(\bf A^{-1}=\) [[input:ans1]].&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;[[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div&gt;(b) \(\bf B^{-1}=\) [[input:ans2]].&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;[[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;FEEDBACK&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;To find the inverse of \(\bf A = {@A@}\) using the determinant method will require four steps.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;First we find the determinant of \(\bf A.\)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[ \det(\bf A) = {@detA@} .\]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Since \(\det(\bf A) \neq 0\) the inverse of \(\bf A\) exists.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now, we replace each element of \(\bf A\) by its cofactor.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The cofactor of \({\bf A}_{ij}\) is the determinant of the matrix that remains when row \(i\) and column \(j\) are removed, multiplied by \((-1)^{i+j}\). So we have,&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;{@cofactorsA@}.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Then we transpose the result to obtain the adjoint matrix:&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(\bf adj(A) =&amp;nbsp;{@cofactorsA@}^{T} = {@adjA@}.\)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Finally we obtain \(\bf A^{-1}\) using the following formula:&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(\bf A^{-1} = \frac{1}{\det(A)} adj(A) = \frac{1}{@detA@} {@adjA@} = {@ta1@}.\)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The method can be used to determine \(\bf B^{-1}\)&amp;nbsp;similarly, which gives \(B^{-1} = {@ta2@}.\)&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
